95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.101dd1dd-b42d-45bd-90d5-3ae9e60eda49.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.12b3dfea-156b-4107-9e0e-9efd80c252e5.description=
Retrieves row indexes if the row satisfies the specified condition in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\: 
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet.
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row.
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    columnIndextoQuery - The column index to search in.
    operator - The math operators. 
Valid values\: \=\=, \!\= for string comparison; \=\=, \!\=, <,<\=,>,>\= for numeric comparison.
Default vaue\: \=\=
    value - The value to search in the specified column. If left blank, it means an empty value.

Results\: 
    returnResult - This is the primary result. Return a list of row indexes that satisfied the specified condition.
    rowsCount - The number of the row indexes returned.

Responses\: 
    success - The row indexes were retrieved successfully. 
    failure - Failed to retrieve the row indexes.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. Value in date type has to be in the format of "YYYY/MM/DD", "YYYY/DD/MM HH\:MM\:SS" or "YYYY/MM/DD HH\:MM".
4. Value in time type has to be in the format of "HH\:MM\:SS" or "HH\:MM".
5. If there's any merged region existed in the worksheet, the cells in the merged region are not considered except the top left cell.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.15b24577-220e-42da-9b0a-0e20adba2e82.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-yyyy HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.1ec5b1c6-fc58-4b28-a0a2-f3dbee54fed3.description=

95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.455565a6-bf97-424b-ad59-0259764959a8.description=
Compares two dates. If the locale is not specified, the inputs must be in the format of date/time format of OO Central Server's, which is dependent of Java Locale. You can use flow " Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format. If locale is specified, the inputs must be in the format of the locale. If locale is not specified, then default locale will be used. In order to compare UNIX timestamps use 'unix' for localeLang input.

Inputs\:
    d1 - The first date. 
Value format\:
Format is dependant on the 'localeLang' and 'localeCountry' inputs and, if the inputs are not provided, on the default locale. 
- If localeLang\="en" and localeCountry\="US" the format is "MMMM d, yyyy h\:mm\:ss a z".
- If no localeLang is provided and the default locale is English the format is "MMM d, yyyy h\:mm\:ss a".
This is the meaning of the above pattern letters\:
y	Year, Examples\:	1996; 96
M	Month in year, Examples\:	July; Jul; 07
d	Day in month, Examples\:	10
a	Am/pm marker, Examples\:	PM
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12), Ex.\:	12
m	Minute in hour, Examples\:	30
s	Second in minute, Examples\:	55
z	Time zone, Examples\:	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Examples\:
If locale is not specified and the US default locale is English, the format could be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM" or "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM PST". If localeLang\="en" and localeCountry\="US", the format should be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM PST".
    d2 - The second date.  It must be in the format that is the same as d1.
    threshold -The number of milliseconds around each date that still allows the dates to be considered equal.
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ignored.

Responses\:
    before - If d1 is before d2.
    equal - If d1 is < d2 + threshold and d1 > d2-threshold.
    after - If d1 is after d2.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Results\:
    The value of d1-d2 in milliseconds.

Note\:
    1. if localeLang is specified the date "LONG" style is used but if it is not specified the "DEFAULT" style is used. Example\: For U.S. Locale "LONG" style is "June 30, 2009 7\:03\:47 AM PDT" and "DEFAULT" style is "Jun 30, 2009 7\:03\:47 AM"
    2. For UNIX timestamps, just use the value 'unix' for input LocaleLang and the operation will treat the input dates as UNIX timestamps. In this case localeCountry input is ignored.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.485d5795-b858-4c68-a255-5b83465acf00.description=And it does nothing... 95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.4e8290e4-08f3-42aa-b86b-038ff52b1022.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.64991e72-585c-4963-b180-a52923a23ed3.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.

95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.7d5c958b-8069-49eb-a20e-c3c953c9d03d.description=
Creates a blank Excel spreadsheet document. The format of the document (XLS or XLSX) depends on the extension used by the file.

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetNames - A delimited list of names that will be created as worksheets in the document. 
Default value\: Sheet1,Sheet2,Sheet3.
    delimiter - The character used to delimit worksheet names.
Default value\: comma (,)

Result\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns a success or failure message.

Responses\:
    success - A new Excel document is created successfully.
    failure - Failed to create a new Excel document.

Notes\:
XLSM format is not supported.

95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.87578efb-e4da-4d7e-a024-cb198adc0c3b.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.9591d0c7-8184-4e09-92ee-3e7d95fe47a6.description=
Retrieves the cell data with specified row index and column index in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet. 
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row. 
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: Yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    rowIndex - A list of row indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default Value\: from the index of the first row  to the index of the last row in the Excel worksheet.
    columnIndex - A list of column indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: from 0 to the index of the last column in the Excel worksheet.
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the rows of the returnResult.
Default value\: | (pipe)
    columnDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the columns of the returnResult.
Default value\: , (comma)

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the cell data retrieved from Excel document.
    header - A delimited list of column names of data being returned if hasHeader is set to Yes. 
    rowsCount - The number of the rows returned.
    columnsCount - The number of the columns returned.

Responses\:
    success - The cell data was retrieved successfully.
    failure - Failed to retireve the cell data.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. For the indexes in rowIndex input that is less than the first data row index or greater than the last row index in the worksheet, the operation trims those row indexes.
4. For the indexes in columnIndex input that is less than 0 or greater than the last column index in a row, the operation trims those column indexes.
5. The cell data with fraction format shows as double value in returnResult.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.a3dd041f-31e7-4366-b9c5-697a04623507.description=
Compares two dates. If the locale is not specified, the inputs must be in the format of date/time format of OO Central Server's, which is dependent of Java Locale. You can use flow " Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format. If locale is specified, the inputs must be in the format of the locale. If locale is not specified, then default locale will be used. In order to compare UNIX timestamps use 'unix' for localeLang input.

Inputs\:
    d1 - The first date. 
Value format\:
Format is dependant on the 'localeLang' and 'localeCountry' inputs and, if the inputs are not provided, on the default locale. 
- If localeLang\="en" and localeCountry\="US" the format is "MMMM d, yyyy h\:mm\:ss a z".
- If no localeLang is provided and the default locale is English the format is "MMM d, yyyy h\:mm\:ss a".
This is the meaning of the above pattern letters\:
y	Year, Examples\:	1996; 96
M	Month in year, Examples\:	July; Jul; 07
d	Day in month, Examples\:	10
a	Am/pm marker, Examples\:	PM
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12), Ex.\:	12
m	Minute in hour, Examples\:	30
s	Second in minute, Examples\:	55
z	Time zone, Examples\:	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Examples\:
If locale is not specified and the US default locale is English, the format could be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM" or "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM PST". If localeLang\="en" and localeCountry\="US", the format should be "July 12, 2006 4\:23\:20 PM PST".
    d2 - The second date.  It must be in the format that is the same as d1.
    threshold -The number of milliseconds around each date that still allows the dates to be considered equal.
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ignored.

Responses\:
    before - If d1 is before d2.
    equal - If d1 is < d2 + threshold and d1 > d2-threshold.
    after - If d1 is after d2.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Results\:
    The value of d1-d2 in milliseconds.

Note\:
    1. if localeLang is specified the date "LONG" style is used but if it is not specified the "DEFAULT" style is used. Example\: For U.S. Locale "LONG" style is "June 30, 2009 7\:03\:47 AM PDT" and "DEFAULT" style is "Jun 30, 2009 7\:03\:47 AM"
    2. For UNIX timestamps, just use the value 'unix' for input LocaleLang and the operation will treat the input dates as UNIX timestamps. In this case localeCountry input is ignored.
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.aac52a47-469b-4c55-9d57-52f41ea3d668.description=
Adds rows of data to an Excel document. This operation can be used to add/insert/update data to worksheets and documents. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The worksheet to which the data should be added.
Default value\: Sheet1 
    headerData - A delimited list of column names. If left blank, the document will not have a header for the data.
    rowData - A delimited list of data.
    columnDelimiter - A delimiter used to separate columns of rowData and headerData.
Default value\: comma (,)
    rowsDelimiter - A delimiter used to separate rows of rowData.
Default value\: pipe (|)
    rowIndex - A list of row indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: append from the last row of the Excel worksheet.
    columnIndex - A list of column indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: from index 0 in the Excel worksheet.
    overwriteData - true if existing data should be overwritten.
Default value\: false


Result\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the number of rows that were added.

Responses\:
    success - One or more rows of data were added successfully.
    failure - Failed to add rows of data to the Excel document.


Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. If rowIndex input is not empty the row count must be equal to the row count of rowData.
3. If columnIndex input is not empty the column count must be equal to the column count of rowData
4. If columnIndex input is not empty it's used for every row that is added.
5. If the rowData contains a numeric value, the cell modified is set to numeric type.
6. There's a limitation that if the rowData is a date or time value, the operation treats it as a string value.
7. If there's any change in the worksheet, all values of formula type cells are updated.
8. If there's any merged region existed in the worksheet, only the top left cell can be modified.

Examples\:
1. To add a header and a single row of data to an Excel document using comma as the column delimiter, input should be given as follows-
headerData - columnName1,columnName2,columnName3
rowData - value1,value2,value3
columnDelimiter - ,

2. To add a header and multiple rows of data to an Excel document using comma (,) as the column delimiter and pipe (|) as the row delimiter, input should be given as follows-
headerData 	- columnName1,columnName2,columnName3
rowData - value11,value12,value13|value21,value22,value23|value31,value32,value33
columnDelimiter - ,
rowDelimiter	- |

3. To add multiple rows of data on multiple columns to an Excel document using comma (,) as the column delimiter and pipe (|) as the row delimiter, input should be given as follows-
rowData - value11,value12,value13|value21,value22,value23|value31,value32,value33
columnDelimiter - ,
rowDelimiter	- |
rowIndex - 1,3,4
columnIndex - 3\:5
95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.b05b05d5-6d1f-494b-adc2-281a56a92279.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja

95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.description=Identify the active row in VMGD when Fixed Flag is set to No. Inputs\: screenVMGD - The screen dump of VMGD. worksheetName - The name of the worksheet in Excel spreadsheet. excelFileName - The path and filename of the Excel spreadsheet. Eg\: C\:\Temp\filename.xlsx Returns\: rowsCount - Total number of rows in VMGD rowsIndex - Row numbers where SHDE entries are present. activeLine - The line number where values need to be pushed. Responses\: success - The flow completed as stated in description. failure - The flow failed to complete. 95b6ea05-f5cc-49b7-ba87-723b02f5aa4c.e17f399c-a41e-4524-9c4d-b47326e4f578.description=
Retrieves the cell data with specified row index and column index in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet. 
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row. 
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: Yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    rowIndex - A list of row indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default Value\: from the index of the first row  to the index of the last row in the Excel worksheet.
    columnIndex - A list of column indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: from 0 to the index of the last column in the Excel worksheet.
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the rows of the returnResult.
Default value\: | (pipe)
    columnDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the columns of the returnResult.
Default value\: , (comma)

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the cell data retrieved from Excel document.
    header - A delimited list of column names of data being returned if hasHeader is set to Yes. 
    rowsCount - The number of the rows returned.
    columnsCount - The number of the columns returned.

Responses\:
    success - The cell data was retrieved successfully.
    failure - Failed to retireve the cell data.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. For the indexes in rowIndex input that is less than the first data row index or greater than the last row index in the worksheet, the operation trims those row indexes.
4. For the indexes in columnIndex input that is less than 0 or greater than the last column index in a row, the operation trims those column indexes.
5. The cell data with fraction format shows as double value in returnResult.

Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
